§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We bound the probability ⦉

  ‖ that a random variance ⦉

  ‖ deviates from its mean ⦉

  ‖ using its variance. ⦉
⦉

§ Result ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ Let $f$ be a ⦉

  ‖ square-integrable ⦉

  ‖ real-valued ⦉

  ‖ random variable ⦉

  ‖ on the probability ⦉

  ‖ space $(X, 𝒜, μ)$. ⦉

  ‖ Then for $t > 0$,
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ μ(\abs{f - 𝗘(f)} ≥ t) ≤ \frac{\var f}{t^2}. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
  <proof>
    ‖ The set ⦉

    ‖ $\abs{f - 𝗘(f)} ≥ t$ ⦉

    ‖ is ⦉

    ‖ $\Set*{x ∈ X}{ \abs{f(x) - 𝗘(f)} ≥ t}$. ⦉

    ‖ This set is ⦉

    ‖ $\Set*{x ∈ X}{({f(x) - 𝗘(f)})^2 ≥ t^2}$. ⦉

    ‖ By using the non-negative inequality
      ◇ ⦊
        ‖ μ(\Set*{x ∈ X}{({f(x) - 𝗘(f)})^2 ≥ t^2}) ≤ \frac{𝗘(f -
          𝗘(f))}{t^2}. ⦉
      ⦉⦉

    ‖ We recognize the numerator of the right ⦉

    ‖ hand side as the variance. ⦉
  </proof>
</statement>
¶ ⦊
  ‖ The above is also called ❬Chebychev's Inequality❭. ⦉
⦉

